<font color="#FF0000">RACISM IN VIETNAM &amp; MAYA'S ART</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jan  8 23:44:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
1-To Mr Bach; Among other things, I spent 10 months on and off special court martial duty besides being assigned to the brigade intelligence company. Have a rather good idea of what our troops were both capable of and actually did. Rapes were no more common than back in the states among the same number of men in the same age bracket. While it's nothing to be proud of, a whole lot of fornication was going on night and day, mostly with the large population of prostitutes, with whom the troops were on occasion rude and crude. The chief expression of racism towards oriental women was expressed in the preferential choice of most single soldiers for Australia as their R&amp;R site because there were &quot;Round Eyes&quot; there. I might point out that nobody has a monopoly on racism. The most virulently anti-black person I ever met was a young Chinese lady in Singapore. <br>
2-To &quot;The Vet&quot;; Whatever your personal feelings about the Wall, there is no denying that the experience of the place has resulted in the healing of hundreds of your fellow veterans. Even if it was the ugliest, most god-awful creation on the planet, it would be worth 1000X it's weight in gold for that alone. If you still can't give it a rest, may God have mercy on your heart. 
<p><code>-- turtle@plantaganet.com  (Gerald Alan Ney, the Herd, 68-69) </code><p>


